The {{nihongo|'''Yōrō River'''|養老川|Yōrōgawa}} is a river in [[:en:Chiba Prefecture|Chiba Prefecture]], [[:en:Japan|Japan]]. It is {{convert|73.4|km|mi|sp=us}} in length and has a drainage area of {{convert|260|km2|sqmi|sp=us}}. Under the Rivers Act of 1906 the Yōrō is designated as a Class 2 River. The Yōrō originates near [[Mount Kiyosumi]] on the border of Amatsukominato area of [[:en:Kamogawa, Chiba|Kamogawa]] and [[:en:Ōtaki, Chiba|Ōtaki]], and then passes through Ōtaki and [[:en:Ichihara, Chiba|Ichihara]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei (日本歴史地名大系 “Compendium of Japanese Historical Place Names”) |title=Yōrō-gawa |url=http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |access-date=2011-03-01 |year=2011 |publisher=Netto Adobansusha |location=Tokyo |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |archive-date=August 25, 2007 }}</ref>
The [[Yōrō Ravine]] and [[Awamata Falls]] are located in the upper part of the Yōrō, and it meets the [[Koshikiya River]], the [[Heizō River]], and the [[Uchida River]] at its midpoint. Land around the middle and lower parts of the Yōrō have been developed for [[rice]] production. The river flows through significant parts of the [[:en:Bōsō Hill Range|Bōsō Hill Range]] before it empties into [[Tokyo Bay]] in the Goi and Iwazaki districts of Ichihara. Land reclamation at the mouth of the Yōrō is a component of the [[:en:Keiyō Industrial Zone|Keiyō Industrial Zone]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Japan |title=Yōrōgawa |url=http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |access-date=2011-12-06 |year=2011 |publisher=Netto Adobansusha |location=Tokyo |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |archive-date=August 25, 2007 }}</ref> The [[:en:Kominato Line|Kominato Line]] of the [[:en:Kominato Railway|Kominato Railway]] roughly follows the path of the Yōrō and provides access to many of the tourist destinations along the river, including mountains, [[:en:Waterfalls|Waterfalls]], and an [[:en:Onsen|Onsen]] [[:en:Hot spring|Hot spring]].

[[File:Yōrō Valley 01.jpg|thumb|View of Yōrō River from the Hōei Bridge, Ichihara, Chiba]]

